<span id="freeTextContainer743894236813229692">Rating: 3.5* of five<br/><br/>This is #12 in the Harry Bosch series of mystery/thrillers, and it&apos;s the last one I will be reading. I just got worn down by the sameness of it all. It&apos;s what makes series books appealing, on the one hand, that comfortable familiarity; but too much of it loosens my grip on the give-a-damn lever.<br/><br/>Now that Harry&apos;s in the unsolved crimes unit, he runs across a 13-year-old case of his that&apos;s bugged him and worried him because he feels sure there&apos;s something he and/or his partner m</span>
  <span id="freeText743894236813229692" style="display:none">Rating: 3.5* of five<br /><br />This is #12 in the Harry Bosch series of mystery/thrillers, and it's the last one I will be reading. I just got worn down by the sameness of it all. It's what makes series books appealing, on the one hand, that comfortable familiarity; but too much of it loosens my grip on the give-a-damn lever.<br /><br />Now that Harry's in the unsolved crimes unit, he runs across a 13-year-old case of his that's bugged him and worried him because he feels sure there's something he and/or his partner missed. <br /><br />Enter a convicted killer facing death, willing to cop to the crime. Trouble is, Harry's not at all sure he did it.<br /><br />So there you have it. You know the whole story. Don't flag me for spoilering, either, because all that's in the flap copy. Now you see why I am done with the series: The basics are good, but the *oomph* that could sustain me over the long haul is gone.</span>
