    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2436790721" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2436790721" />
    <a title="Kevin Dowson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/75375256-kevin-dowson"><img alt="Kevin Dowson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1570436987p2/75375256.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2436790721?book_show_action=true">Jul 09, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kevin Dowson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kevin Dowson" href="/user/show/75375256-kevin-dowson">Kevin Dowson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2436790721" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16234852750100757906">The 12th Bosch book, and once again a collaboration with FBI Agent Rachel Walling. In fact, this book is probably less &quot;Bosch&quot; than some because there is quite a bit of focus on the exchanges between the two of them. Not a bad thing, but I feel it doesn&apos;t have some of the darkness of previous stories, at least concerning Harry himself.<br/><br/>As for the plot, that&apos;s plenty dark. A 13-year old murder, one which has kept drawing Harry back in time and again over the years, suddenly opens wide and Harry an</span>
  <span id="freeText16234852750100757906" style="display:none">The 12th Bosch book, and once again a collaboration with FBI Agent Rachel Walling. In fact, this book is probably less "Bosch" than some because there is quite a bit of focus on the exchanges between the two of them. Not a bad thing, but I feel it doesn't have some of the darkness of previous stories, at least concerning Harry himself.<br /><br />As for the plot, that's plenty dark. A 13-year old murder, one which has kept drawing Harry back in time and again over the years, suddenly opens wide and Harry and his partner Kiz are called in to review the case in light of a shock confession. To make matters worse, it seems Harry and his partner at the time messed up and let the killer slip through their fingers. The confessed killer can finally tell Harry where the missing girl's final resting place is, and allow him to bring peace to her tortured parents after all these years, but Harry isn't feeling it, and he doesn't know why. Has he finally started losing that uncanny instinct?<br /><br />What starts as a pretty standard procedural suddenly and unexpectedly bursts into life and, as usual, whichever turn Bosch makes seems that it can only end badly.He's going to do things his way but who is playing who? And who will get caught in the crossfire?<br /><br />Echo Park has all the ingredients you expect and demand from a Bosch story. I wouldn't rate it as one of the very best, but that still leaves it in the pretty damned good category. If anything it was the last 10% of the book that left me a little unfulfilled, but the interaction between Bosch and other Connelly characters, which seems to be more and more of a feature over time, adds another dimension. And the plot, as ever, was well thought out and well constructed. A healthy 4 stars, and on to the next instalment.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16234852750100757906" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

